GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
S 1
SENATE BILL 535
Short Title: Regulate Hemp-Derived Beverages. (Public)
Sponsors: Senators Moffitt, Johnson, and Lazzara (Primary Sponsors).
Referred to: Rules and Operations of the Senate
March 26, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO REGULATE NONALCOHOLIC HEMP-DERIVED BEVERAGES.
3 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
4 SECTION 1. G.S. 18B-101 reads as rewritten:
5 "§ 18B-101. Definitions.
6 As used in this Chapter, unless the context requires otherwise:
7 …
8 (4) "Alcoholic beverage" means any beverage containing at least one-half of one
9 percent (0.5%) alcohol by volume, including malt beverages, unfortified wine,
10 fortified wine, spirituous liquor, mixed beverages, and any alcohol
11 consumable. This term does not include hemp-derived beverages.
12 …
13 (7b) "Hemp-derived beverage" means a nonalcoholic beverage fit for human
14 consumption that contains hemp, as defined in G.S. 90-87, but may contain
15 concentrations of other hemp-derived cannabinoids in excess of that amount.
16 (7c) "Hemp-derived cannabinoid" means any phytocannabinoid found in hemp,
17 including delta 9 tetrahydrocannabinol (delta 9 THC), tetrahydrocannabinolic
18 acid (THCA), cannabidiol (CBD), cannabidiolic acid (CBDA), cannabinol
19 (CBN), cannabigerol (CBG), cannabichromene (CBC), cannabicyclol (CBL),
20 cannabivarin (CBV), tetrahydrocannabivarin (THCV), cannabidivarin
21 (CBDV), cannabicitran (CBT), delta 7 tetrahydrocannabinol (delta 7 THC),
22 delta 8 tetrahydrocannibinol (delta 8 THC), or delta 10 tetrahydrocannibinol
23 (delta 10 THC). This term also includes any synthetic cannabinoid derived
24 from hemp and contained in a hemp-derived consumable product.
25 (7b)(7d) "Historic ABC establishment" means a restaurant or hotel that meets all of
26 the following requirements:
27 a. Is on the national register of historic places or located within a State
28 historic district.
29 b. Is a property designed to attract local, State, national, and international
30 tourists located on a State Route (SR) and with a property line located
31 within 1.5 miles of the intersection of a designated North Carolina
32 scenic byway as defined in G.S. 136-18(31).
33 c. Is located within 15 miles of a national scenic highway.
34 d. Is located in a county in which the on-premises sale of malt beverages
35 or unfortified wine is authorized in two or more cities in the county.
*S535-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (7c)(7e) "Keg" means a portable container designed to hold and dispense 7.75
2 gallons or more of malt beverage.
3 …
4 (9) "Malt beverage" means beer, lager, malt liquor, ale, porter, and any other
5 brewed or fermented beverage or alcohol consumable except unfortified or
6 fortified wine as defined by this Chapter, containing at least one-half of one
7 percent (0.5%), and not more than fifteen percent (15%), alcohol by volume.
8 Any malt beverage containing more than six percent (6%) alcohol by volume
9 shall bear a label clearly indicating the alcohol content of the malt beverage.
10 This term also includes hemp-derived beverages.
11 …."
12 SECTION 2. G.S. 18B-102 reads as rewritten:
13 "§ 18B-102. Manufacture, sale, etc., forbidden except as expressly authorized.
14 (a) General Prohibition. – It shall be unlawful for any person to manufacture, sell,
15 transport, import, deliver, furnish, purchase, consume, or possess any alcoholic beverages except
16 as authorized by the ABC law.
17 (a1) Powdered Alcohol Prohibition. – It shall be unlawful for any person to manufacture,
18 sell, transport, import, deliver, furnish, purchase, consume, or possess powdered alcohol.
19 (a2) Hemp-Derived Beverages. – Except as otherwise provided in this Chapter, it shall be
20 unlawful for any person to manufacture, sell, transport, import, deliver, furnish, purchase,
21 consume, or possess hemp-derived beverages.
22 (b) Violation a Class 1 Misdemeanor. – Unless a different punishment is otherwise
23 expressly stated, any person who violates any provision of this Chapter shall be guilty of a Class
24 1 misdemeanor. In addition the court may impose the provisions of G.S. 18B-202 and of
25 G.S. 18B-503, 18B-504, and 18B-505."
26 SECTION 3. G.S. 18B-206 reads as rewritten:
27 "§ 18B-206. Standards for alcoholic beverages.beverages and hemp-derived beverages.
28 (a) Authority to Set Standards. – The Commission may set standards and adopt rules for
29 alcoholic beverages and hemp-derived beverages to protect the public against alcoholic
30 beverages or hemp-derived beverages containing harmful or impure substances, alcoholic
31 beverages or hemp-derived beverages containing an improper balance of substances as
32 determined by the Commission, spurious or imitation alcoholic beverages, beverages or
33 hemp-derived beverages, and alcoholic beverages or hemp-derived beverages unfit for human
34 consumption. In setting standards and in issuing rules relating to them, alcoholic beverages, the
35 Commission may follow federal guidelines for standards of identity, labeling and advertising
36 contained in Title 27 of the Code of Federal Regulations, or may adopt more restrictive standards.
37 (b) Effective Date of Standards. – A person possessing alcoholic beverages or
38 hemp-derived beverages which do not meet a new standard set by the Commission shall have 60
39 days after the effective date of the standard to sell or otherwise dispose of those alcoholic
40 beverages.beverages or hemp-derived beverages.
41 (c) Testing. – The Commission may test malt beverages, unfortified wine, fortified wine,
42 and spirituous liquor possessed or offered for sale in this State to determine whether they meet
43 the standards set by the Commission. If the Commission chooses to test an alcoholic beverage,
44 beverage or hemp-derived beverage, that test may be performed by the Commission, the
45 Commission may arrange for the State Chemist to perform the testing, or the Commission may
46 have the testing performed in some other manner. The manufacturer of tested alcoholic beverages
47 or hemp-derived beverages shall pay the costs of the test. In lieu of testing an alcoholic beverage,
48 beverage or hemp-derived beverages, the Commission may rely on testing by a federal agency
49 or an agency of another state or may accept test results from a federal agency, an agency of
50 another state, or the manufacturer of the alcoholic beverage or hemp-derived beverage or his or
